  "summary": "date-uuid executes remote VBScript dropper on require()",
  "details": "Package advertises itself as a date-based UUID generator but, on require()/import, lib/bootstrap.js invokes extractDateISO() which reads the installer's README.md, decodes two base64 fragments at fixed line numbers (120/123) marked 'api1:'/'api2:' to assemble a remote URL, fetches that URL, writes the body to os.tmpdir() as temp_\u003ctimestamp\u003e.vbs, and executes it via child_process.exec on Windows. The file extension is constructed as '.v'+'b'+'s' to evade literal-string matching, and the URL is held out-of-band in README steganography rather than in the package source. This behavior is unrelated to the advertised UUID functionality and fires at module load, before any UUID API is called. The name 'date-uuid' appears chosen to attract developers searching for time-based UUID libraries (uuid v7, uuidv7, time-uuid).",
